Sthānā in l1 is followed by a space with some marks in it. There doesn't seem to be anything like a halanta T here, but one of the marks may be a punctuation dash. The marks also resemble the unusual visarga in l3.
--><!--
In aśvamedha-yājinaḥ in l2, dhayā are squeezed very close together. It is quite probable that ya or yā was inscribed first, then the left-hand part of the ya was corrected to dha; the right-hand part of ya was changed to the centre of a new yā, adding the right-hand part to it.
--><!--
The halanta Ṭ in l2 is subscript, but full-sized, without a boxhead.
--><!--
The visarga before the hole in l3 looks unusual: it consists of two curving horizontal lines, both like a J rotated 90 degrees clockwise (and without a serif), the top one shorter. This looks very much like several punctuation marks in this document (line 1, line 13) but cannot be a punctuation mark here; there are also several definite visargas that look like this (l14).
--><!--
As Mirashi notes, the boxhead of nta in atyanta, l3, is not completed: the bottom side is missing.
--><!--
The punctuation mark in l3 is a dot.
--><!--
In l5 after °abhiṣiktānām, the phrase daśāśvamedhāvabhr̥tha-snātānām was omitted, as noted by Mirashi. As it happens, Mirashi in CII5 also omits bhāraśivānām, though he does print the word in EI22.
--><!--
The lower j of ārjjava in l7 seems to be unfinished, consisting of just the vertical and the top horizontal stroke.
--><!--
The single punctuation mark after vacanā in l13 is much like the one after sthānā in l1: a curved dash and possibly something more above it. Can these be very unusual halanta Ts?
--></p>
